00:48:52,022 --> 00:48:54,439
Guest: I think we can say one magical word about one of them.

596
00:48:54,882 --> 00:48:55,696
Emily: Air pirates.

597
00:48:56,660 --> 00:48:57,440
Rym: That's two words.

598
00:48:57,722 --> 00:48:57,908
Guest: Oh, no.

599
00:49:00,364 --> 00:49:01,659
Emily: Air pirates and airships.

600
00:49:01,944 --> 00:49:02,840
Emily: Be prepared.

601
00:49:03,880 --> 00:49:13,140
Rym: So having actually brought this game to completion from the beginning as kind of people just getting into the gaming industry, what did you learn?

602
00:49:15,403 --> 00:49:18,800
Rym: Like, what would you have done differently from the start making this game?

603
00:49:19,160 --> 00:49:27,137
Guest: Well, one, I have a much greater grasp of how much complexity you can actually expect people to pick up on, especially for a little browser game.

604
00:49:28,980 --> 00:49:33,400
Guest: And it has taught me to rein in my ambitions for the future.

605
00:49:35,320 --> 00:49:37,240
Emily: And I don't know.

606
00:49:37,360 --> 00:49:44,680
Emily: As far as I'm concerned, like I said, it was a very simple game as far as art asset creation.

607
00:49:45,020 --> 00:49:52,660
Emily: But I think one thing that really left an impression on me is, you know, GUI design is incredibly important.

608
00:49:53,183 --> 00:49:59,360
Emily: And I should definitely start earlier in the design process with developing a GUI.

609
00:49:59,640 --> 00:50:08,660
Emily: And like each iteration, each change in gameplay, you've got to adjust your ideas of the layout of the interface.

610
00:50:09,581 --> 00:50:14,520
Emily: And I guess the interface, we really started working on that way late in the game.

611
00:50:14,980 --> 00:50:18,380
Emily: We had like a very standard boxes thing--.

612
00:50:18,380 --> 00:50:21,098
Guest: It was crappy with the [INAUDIBLE] --for a long time, yeah.

613
00:50:21,780 --> 00:50:41,760
Emily: So I think every time Alex changes a gameplay element, I think I'll also have to look at it, and along with our other design people like Austin, and kind of brainstorm about how can we make this particular iteration very intuitive and playable.

614
00:50:42,361 --> 00:50:49,138
Guest: If you're one of those aspiring game developers out there, I have a piece of very, I think, cogent advice for you.

615
00:50:51,340 --> 00:50:58,439
Guest: Inevitably, if you're a wannabe game developer, you have in mind some huge sprawling game.

616
00:50:59,900 --> 00:51:11,539
Guest: Statistically, from what I've seen, it's very likely to be an RPG, but it doesn't have to be, with a million really cool and novel mechanics, and really great graphics, and a really awesome story, and wonderful music.

617
00:51:12,427 --> 00:51:13,020
Guest: And that's great.

618
00:51:13,100 --> 00:51:17,119
Guest: And that's a great thing to shoot for, but you have to understand you're not going to make it on your first try.

619
00:51:18,506 --> 00:51:27,999
Guest: It's kind of like-- You have to be willing to focus on the things that are really important about the game, the most important elements, whatever they are.

620
00:51:28,441 --> 00:51:29,278
Guest: Make those work.

621
00:51:29,740 --> 00:51:33,860
Guest: And if you can add stuff that works with them rather than against them, great.

622
00:51:34,300 --> 00:51:36,740
Guest: But if you can't, leave it small and perfect.

623
00:51:37,540 --> 00:51:40,700
Emily: Well, it's kind of like how I was when I first entered film school.

624
00:51:40,860 --> 00:51:43,780
Emily: It's like I really wanted to do this big epic feature thing.

625
00:51:44,200 --> 00:51:53,700
Emily: And then I realized, no, just concentrate on getting a damn good three minutes worth of footage, and then start to increase your ambition.

626
00:51:54,683 --> 00:51:57,440
Emily: But yeah, start small and start solid.

627
00:51:58,282 --> 00:52:04,580
Emily: Come up with something really well thought out, and then you can start to work your way up the ladder.

628
00:52:04,721 --> 00:52:09,879
Guest: Do not allow yourself the luxury of saying, I know this, and this, and this.

629
00:52:10,220 --> 00:52:10,687
Guest: This one part.

630
00:52:10,708 --> 00:52:12,540
Guest: I'm kind of fuzzy on, but I'll figure it out later.

631
00:52:12,889 --> 00:52:12,995
Guest: No.

632
00:52:13,540 --> 00:52:15,059
Guest: Sit down and figure that part out now.

633
00:52:15,905 --> 00:52:16,880
Scott: Or else it'd be Dwarf Fortress.

634
00:52:17,660 --> 00:52:17,931
Emily: I don't know.

635
00:52:18,862 --> 00:52:20,799
Guest: I don't think that's where Dwarf Fortress has issues.

636
00:52:21,322 --> 00:52:22,019
Guest: I don't think so.

637
00:52:22,583 --> 00:52:23,216
Guest: It has issues.

638
00:52:23,520 --> 00:52:23,974
Guest: I won't deny.

