648
00:52:49,280 --> 00:52:52,259
Emily: We were all sitting in front of the TV that I played the beta beta version.

649
00:52:52,521 --> 00:52:57,520
Scott: And it seemed kind of because like I would put out a whole bunch of balls and they would die really slowly.

650
00:52:57,701 --> 00:53:00,980
Scott: And it was sort of like it was that, you know, it was like I was.

651
00:53:01,101 --> 00:53:02,600
Scott: I couldn't tell if I was winning or losing.

652
00:53:03,042 --> 00:53:05,359
Scott: And, you know, I could put so much stuff out.

653
00:53:05,521 --> 00:53:07,840
Scott: And it was just sort of like this attrition kind of thing.

654
00:53:07,920 --> 00:53:12,940
Scott: But when I played it more recently against Alex, it just sort of got creamed immediately.

655
00:53:13,601 --> 00:53:16,515
Scott: So it was definitely a much tighter game.

656
00:53:16,536 --> 00:53:17,319
Scott: where you can you can.

657
00:53:17,620 --> 00:53:19,579
Scott: It was a very significant winning and losing.

658
00:53:20,360 --> 00:53:23,071
Rym: Well, there's definitely the increasing cost.

659
00:53:23,372 --> 00:53:31,180
Rym: as you do one action more and more to discourage the, you know, obvious, make a whole bunch of red and then destroy a whole bunch of stuff with that red.

660
00:53:32,001 --> 00:53:33,820
Emily: I like the increasing price mechanic.

661
00:53:33,980 --> 00:53:34,959
Emily: I think that added a lot.

662
00:53:35,200 --> 00:53:41,520
Scott: I think what it is to sum up what I was saying is that in the earlier version of the game, it felt like your individual moves mattered less.

663
00:53:41,862 --> 00:53:45,439
Scott: And in the more recent one, each move matters a whole lot more.

664
00:53:46,002 --> 00:53:49,040
Scott: And so a wrong move here or there can be the difference.

665
00:53:49,240 --> 00:53:52,600
Scott: So there's actually significant decisions being made all the time.

666
00:53:53,242 --> 00:53:56,620
Scott: And that is that is definitely a good thing in a game that I like, at least.

667
00:53:56,740 --> 00:53:57,700
Scott: I don't know about other people.

668
00:53:57,940 --> 00:54:04,240
Guest: I think it was Sid Meyer who said the immortal phrase that every game designer should know a game is a series of interesting decisions.

669
00:54:04,623 --> 00:54:05,440
Scott: Yes, that is correct.

670
00:54:05,720 --> 00:54:14,200
Rym: I guess I I feel like it'll shine the most in multiplayer because knowing that there's a human making these important decisions on the other side always means a lot to me.

671
00:54:14,380 --> 00:54:17,959
